# Generated by: python tools/generate_benchmark.py --output tests/tasknet_files/benchmark/seqforce_10.tn sequential --tasks 10 --use-windows
#
# Sequential Force Benchmark (Resources + Time Windows)
# 
# Configuration:
# - 10 tasks (7 required, 3 optional)
# - 1 timeline (battery)
# - Sequential ordering via BOTH resources AND time windows
# - Variable durations [1, 6]
# - Time horizon: 200
# 
# Design principle:
#   Like seq benchmarks BUT with added temporal constraints
#   Tests scheduler with BOTH resource dependencies AND time windows
# 
# Resource constraints (same as seq):
# - Battery timeline starts at 0
# - T_i requires battery >= 5.0*(i-1)
# - Each task charges battery at +1.0/time
# - Forces T1 → T2 → ... → T10 ordering
# 
# PLUS temporal constraints (added):
# - Each task has start_range and duration_range
# - Windows arranged to prevent overlapping (sequential)
# - duration_range provides scheduling flexibility
# 
# Expected behavior:
# - Tasks execute sequentially (enforced twice: resources + windows)
# - Tests combined resource + temporal reasoning
# - More constrained than seq alone

tasknet SeqForce10 {
  end = 200;

  timelines {
    battery : rate [0.0, 200.0] bounds [0.0, 200.0] = 0.0;
  }

  task T1 {
